{"summary":"Both amendments describe real lineage-correlation defects. The current fallback behavior for legacy rows treats missing run IDs and matching timestamps as identity, which can merge distinct attempts and erase retry history.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-12-5e41079a","decision":"accept","rationale":"find_matching_running_task_run returns a sole open legacy row for a later named start, and record_task_run_start then backfills that existing raw row instead of appending a new attempt. That rewrites an older attempt into the new run_id, keeps the old started_at, and leaves only one visible attempt. For an audit trail that is supposed to preserve retries by run, that silent merge is a correctness bug even if the same path is also useful for idempotent repair."},{"amendment_id":"fr-12-eaae97d7","decision":"accept","rationale":"When either side lacks run_id, TaskRunEntry::same_attempt falls back to started_at equality, and collapse_task_run_attempts merges entries on that basis, including terminal rows with the same outcome. There is no enforced guarantee that started_at is unique per attempt, especially for backward-compatible legacy rows or callers that reuse or truncate timestamps, so distinct retries can collapse into one find_runs_for_bead result. That makes started_at an unsafe surrogate identifier and breaks retry visibility."}]}